statement.p:
The steps on the right below show that the vector \vect{y} is in the span of S, \spn{S}.
                Match the reasons on the left to the step on the right.

                  \vect{y}&=\colvector{1\\3\\2}&S&=\set{\colvector{2\\1\\0},\,\colvector{-3\\1\\2}}

Suppose thatS=\set{
                \colvector{-1 \\ 2 \\ 1},\,
                \colvector{ 3 \\ 1 \\ 2},\,
                \colvector{ 1 \\ 5 \\ 4},\,
                \colvector{-6 \\ 5 \\ 1}
                }.  Let W=\spn{S} and let \vect{y}=\colvector{-5\\3\\0}.  Is \vect{y}\in W?  If so, provide an explicit linear combination that demonstrates this.

Suppose thatS=\set{
                \colvector{-1 \\ 2 \\ 1},\,
                \colvector{ 3 \\ 1 \\ 2},\,
                \colvector{ 1 \\ 5 \\ 4},\,
                \colvector{-6 \\ 5 \\ 1}
                }.  Let W=\spn{S} and let \vect{w}=\colvector{2\\1\\3}.  Is \vect{w}\in W?  If so, provide an explicit linear combination that demonstrates this.

For the matrix A below, find a set of vectors S so that the span of S equals the null space of A, \spn{S}=\nsp{A}.A=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                1 & 1 & 6 & -8\\
                1 & -2 & 0 & 1\\
                -2 & 1 & -6 & 7
                \end{bmatrix}

solution.p:
If the columns of the coefficient matrix from Archetype are named \vect{u}_1,\,\vect{u}_2,\,\vect{u}_3,\,\vect{u}_4 then we can discover the equation (-2)\vect{u}_1+(-3)\vect{u}_2+\vect{u}_3+\vect{u}_4=\zerovectorby building a homogeneous system of equations and viewing a solution to the system as scalars in a linear combination via .  This particular vector equation can be rearranged to read\vect{u}_4=(2)\vect{u}_1+(3)\vect{u}_2+(-1)\vect{u}_3.  This can be interpreted to mean that \vect{u}_4 is unnecessary in \spn{\set{\vect{u}_1,\,\vect{u}_2,\,\vect{u}_3,\,\vect{u}_4}}, so that\spn{\set{\vect{u}_1,\,\vect{u}_2,\,\vect{u}_3,\,\vect{u}_4}}
                =
                \spn{\set{\vect{u}_1,\,\vect{u}_2,\,\vect{u}_3}}.  If we try to repeat this process and find a linear combination of \vect{u}_1,\,\vect{u}_2,\,\vect{u}_3 that equals the zero vector, we will fail.  The required homogeneous system of equations (via ) has only a trivial solution, which will not provide the kind of equation we need to remove one of the three remaining vectors.
